segments.text: General George Beverly, United States Air Force, retired.
Today is Thursday, July 16, 1981.
This is Terry Anderson in Del Rio, Texas.
This is a test.
Today's interview is with Brigadier General George Beverly.
It is July 16, 1981.
This is Terry Henderson.
You were born?
Amarillo, Texas.
Back in May 27, 1897.
Okay.
Let's start by talking about your
grandfather and your parents.
Tell me about your family.
Well, family history goes way back into England, but my grandfather moved from Henderson, Kentucky to Goliad, near Goliad, Texas by ox cart in 1853.
Brought along all his household goods and his slaves

acquired two plantations near Goliad, Texas, and he prospered very well there until the Civil War, which time he lost his slaves and the family had a little difficulty adjusting, of course, and moved up to San Antonio to put the children in school.
And my older brother, I mean his oldest son, my father, had to go to work to help the family out when he was about 12 years old.
So he didn't get a great deal of schooling.
But he became a trail driver when he was about 17.
He went up the trail the first time in 1871 with the herd and then he went up.
Where were they driving the herds?
To Kansas at that time.
I believe they were going into Abilene and the last herd he took up was several years later about I would guess 1877.
He was trail boss at that time.
about 23 years old, which speaks pretty well for his ability.
Sure.
I expect to have about 4,000 head of cattle.
Did he ever tell you about those conditions?
Well yes, he talked about, he didn't talk much about it.
He said they were stopped by Indians in Indian territory and
They would not give the Indians a beef or a steer because that would denote to the Indians that they were worried and maybe afraid of them.
They made the Indians trade blankets for any steers that they gave them.
But otherwise they had no trouble with the Indians.
On his last trip, on the way back, he and his cowboys ran into a bunch of about nine buffalo and they shot some of them and roped some of them and I think they wiped out the whole nine head.
What trail?
Yeah, I think it was the Chisholm Trail, and my grandfather moved to Dodge City with the family in 18, about 1880, or 1870 sometime, and

We went into partnership with Bob Wright, who was mayor of Dodge City and we opened a mercantile store called Wright and Beverly and did a flourishing business with the Texas Trail Drivers there for several years.
That's where my father met my mother.
She lived in Cairo, Illinois and
came out to Dodge City to visit some of her relatives during the summer and that's where they had met her.
Your grandfather met her?
That my father met her.
Oh, okay.
Okay.
My mother, they were married in 1992, moved to Amarillo, Texas.
That's where I was born.
And why'd they move?
Well I don't know.

He was looking for a job I guess and he got a job as manager of the row ranch, R-O-W-E, row ranch at several thousands of acres north of Clarendon and I don't know how many thousand head of cattle they had but it was quite one of the largest ranches in the Panhandle.
He got the job as manager of that, but he moved the family to Amarillo and bought a home there.
And that's where I was born and my older brother and one of my younger brothers.
How many children in the family?
There were five of us.
My father's family, there were eight.
He had seven brothers and sisters.
Our family, I had three brothers and one sister.
How'd you get along with them when you were growing up?
Oh, I didn't get along too well with my older brother, but he was bossy.
And I knocked the front tooth out for him one time when he had me down on the road.
And I just reached back and got a rock and knocked the front tooth out.
And he had to have it replaced.
It cost him about $10, $15 at that time.
But I got along fine with my younger brother.
He was a year and a half younger than I am.
And then my sister was born.
Carlsbad, New Mexico, where after the family had moved from Amarillo to Carlsbad.
Why'd they move down there?
They moved down there on account of my mother's health.
She had tuberculosis and she thought it would be better in climate for her down there and he did too.
So he went to, the whole family moved to Carlsbad in 1902 and
Dad got the job down there as manager of the Turkey Truck Ranch, which was a large ranch between Carlsbad and Roswell, New Mexico.
I don't know if it's still in existence or not, but it was quite a large ranch.
While he was manager of that ranch, he had some trouble with a couple of cowboys and he fired and they threatened to kill him.

So he rode into Roswell and bought himself a .45 single action, and he had to wear that while those boys were in their vicinity, those young, two young men that he fired, but they never did go through with their threat to killing.
Then in 1906, my Uncle Jim and my father bought a ranch and
12 miles west of Channing, Texas, which is close to Dalhart there, between Amarillo and Dalhart.
And it was 12 miles south of Dalhart and 12 miles west of Channing in the Rita Blanca Canyon.
It's called the Old Marshall Place.
and it was right next door to the XIT main headquarters.
Why'd they decide to move back to Texas?
How was your mother's health at that time?
Dad just wanted to get back to Pan Am, I guess, in the ranching business.
Well, they followed along, but while from 1906 to 1910,

mother stayed at Carlsbad and my younger brother Henry and I and the first year in 1906 we went by train up to Channing and stayed on the ranch that summer and my older brother James and mother stayed in Carlsbad where she gave birth to my only sister Beatrice
Then in 1907, 8 and 9, why the whole family went up to Willis Springs Ranch for the summer and went back to Carlsbad for the winter school term.
Then in 1910, why he moved the whole family up to Dalhart, Texas.
That's where I went to high school.
Could you tell me about the type of man your father was?
Well, he always said that his word was as good as his bond.
He was strictly honest and never tried to beat anybody out of anything.
He was not too smart as a businessman or money wise.
We never had much money.
We had enough to eat, and from the time I was eight or 10, I was out helping with the family finances by selling Saturday evening posts and anything else I could, job I could get.
And I took stenography,
in high school and earned money typing for the county clerk and typing up leads at that time and worked for various businessmen there, an abstract company, Ballard Abstract Company.
I saved my money and after I graduated from high school at Ballard, I went to Texas A&M for two years
I paid all my own expenses.
Did you tell me a little bit about your mother?
What type of person she was?
Well, mother was a very beautiful woman.
She was handicapped by the fact that she had a rude, hungry children to feed and didn't have much money.
But she used to buy cornflakes, for instance, by the crate.
feed us on skim milk.
We couldn't afford fresh milk, whole milk.

So the dairyman would sell us a gallon of skim milk for 10 cents and occasionally if he had extra whole milk why he'd just pour in the whole milk instead of the skim milk and that was a real treat for us but that's about that gives you some idea of
the struggles she had in paying the bills.
She played, well at Carlsbad she played the organ for the Episcopal Church and made some money that way.
And at Dalhart she was one time telephone operator up there in the switchboard room with the hardware store at Dalhart.
Was she a hard working woman?
Well, oh yeah, she was a hard worker.
She was a very fine bridge player.
She belonged to the bridge club there in Dalhart and was probably the best bridge player in Dalhart.
She was a pretty good piano player.
She tried to teach me how to play the piano.
but she just didn't have the nervous energy to force me to practice.
I'd rather be out on the sandlot playing football with the boys and sitting in there practicing piano, so I never did learn to play.
I did learn to play the cornet, played in the dial art.
Dan played second coronet, I think.
Who was the authority in the family, your mother or your father?
Mother.
Dad was somebody on the ranch.
Whenever us boys got out of hand to where mother couldn't handle us, she'd get dad to come in and he'd
Of course, he'd give us a licking that would last at least a year.
He had a piece of leather trace, I don't know if you know what they are.
It runs from the horse's collar back to the single tree or double tree.
He had a piece of it about that thick, about that long.
About 18 inches long and about an inch thick?
Oh no, he's about half an inch thick.
Anyway, it was terrific licking he'd give each one of us and that would do us for a year at least.
Mother had a rawhide riding crop that she applied to proper places whenever she got so exasperated she couldn't
stand it any longer, but on the whole I guess we were an average kid.
No meaner than the average.
We were... You mentioned the Episcopal Church.
Was religion important in your upbringing?
Uh, yes.
My mother sent us to Sunday school, and we Presbyterians way back in 400 years.
in Scotland, and we also were, went to the young man, people's, Epworth League, I believe they call it, something like that, the Presbyterian Church, and we went evening service sometime.
I'm not too, I don't remember too much about that except that I do remember I joined the church when I was I guess about 16 or 17 by confession of faith.
We were all baptized when we were babies.
Later on when I quit the Presbyterian on account of the National Council of Churches
I went to a Christian church, the North American Christian Convention, but that was later.
But I had to be dumped, I had to be baptized again, immersed.
Getting back to Texas A&M.
Well, before we move to Texas A&M, I want to ask you another question about your parents.
You had a very successful career rising to the rank of general, and I was wondering in what ways do you think your parents were responsible for that?
Well, I think that both my father and my mother instilled an idea of integrity.
and that we wouldn't lie.
We, in some cases, did occasionally lie, but that was drilled into us to be truthful and honest and have respect for authority.
That's about all I can think of at this time that they instilled into us.
Okay, now let's go to your education, but before we get to A&M, let's talk a little bit about your high school.
What were your favorite subjects?
Well, I was smarter than the average student.
I don't say that egotistically, but
I didn't have enough to keep me interested, to keep up with the class.
I didn't try to excel because I'd rather be out playing baseball or football or something or maybe dreaming, daydreaming, but I breezed through the courses with no trouble at all.
I took up shorthand and typewriting so I could make extra money
It took a year of German.
I liked my German teacher and I enjoyed that course.
I enjoyed ancient history and I liked mathematics.
Would you consider yourself a good student in high school?
I would consider myself a non-problems student.
The teachers had no trouble with me.
I had no trouble keeping up.
Were you involved with a lot of activities and sports?
Uh, Dalhart at that time had about 3,000 people.
Our high school teams were
I played football with a team for instance.
We went down to Amarillo one time to play Amarillo and they beat us 127 to nothing.
Isn't that amazing?
I got kicked behind the ear.
127 to nothing?

I got kicked behind the ear, and I don't remember playing most of the game, but I have a hazy recollection of seeing them, they put their ends way out on the sideline, you know, and then it snapped the ball.
It would go this end down to the, and the ball would go through there, and he'd pick it out and try to cross the goal line for a score.
And we were just helpless.
We were like a bunch of babes in their hands.
At that time, I guess they were about as good as any team in Texas, but in baseball, I was a pretty good high school player.
I played on the Dallard Municipal Team as a catcher in baseball.
As I said, I played in a band and that's
about the extent of my activities there.
Did you consider your work, did you lead, did you consider yourself a leader at that time?
Yes in high school, yeah.
Well in grammar school too.
I was always taking up for mistreated kids, some bullies, there's always bullies you know, and I was a good fighter and I was always protecting the kids who were
The bullies were picking on me, and these bullies were afraid of me.
Why do you think you'd be the one who would stand up for these kids?
I think it's just the nature that I was born in with.
I just hate injustice forcing anything on Eric.
Of course, that comes under injustice to those kids.
Anything in this world I hate, it's injustice.
non-justice.
And so you consider yourself, you see that you started your leadership, your long career of leadership way back when you were a teenager.
In the first grade,
I started it back in the first grade at La Huerta, New Mexico which is suburb of Carlsbad, New Mexico.

We had a one-room schoolhouse there and about 20 students from that area and I think one teacher and their grades over there from the first grade on up to about the seventh and one thing these older boys decided that they're going to find out which one of the

the first and second graders were the best fighters so they cleaned out a pig pen there and this this was a private home they cleaned out this pig pen and then they put two of us in there and we'd fight it make us fight so go over go to it and whoever won why he was in there against the next one and I wound up the winner against all the kids by anywhere near my age
Then I had the first and second grade.
Then I went into Carlsbad to school.
Now were these boxing and kicking matches or were they more wrestling or were you just hitting and elbowing?
Oh, it was just fist cuffs.
When I went into Carlsbad to enter the third grade they gave me a test

made me skip the third grade and put me in the fourth grade with the champion fighter there at Carlsbad I heard about me being the best fighter from the Werda area so he kept pestering me to fight it out see who was the best fighter and he was about that much taller than I was and I dodged him as long as I could but he finally got me cornered in an alley one time
and proceeded to beat me up pretty good.
I finally just quit.
But he was too much for me.
He later became an amateur champion in New Mexico, I think.
But I enjoyed fighting.
I enjoyed anything physical.
Now let's go back to A&M.
Why did you decide to go to Hampton?
I had the reputation down heart of being the toughest school in Texas.
The reputation of making it tough on anybody that would want to try to get in there.
Tough on the freshmen.
And I decided I'd like to go down and try it out.
I got down there and they
Did you ever think of any other alternative schools?
No, I can't think of any.
You never considered going some other place?
No.
Were you interested in the military at this time?
No.
So you never thought of going to West Point?
No.
As a matter of fact, I wasn't much interested in further education, I recall.
I guess mother probably told me I should get a college education, so I always obeyed her.
What did you think when you arrived?
Well, I was a green country boy down there among all those kids from the cities and so forth.
I was on my toes.
I said, what course?
I thought you'd go to college, or you'd take just whatever they gave you, you know, the whole business, just like you would in high school.
You don't go to high school now, but at that time, I took everything I had in high school, and I thought I'd take everything I had in A&M.
I said, well, someone asked me what course I was going to take, and I said, well, I don't know.
What have they got?
Somebody said, well Animal Husbandry is supposed to be the easiest course.
I said, well I believe I'll take that.
I didn't know what it was.
You didn't know what Animal Husbandry was?
No.
I found out later it was out of form.
So I took Animal Husbandry and I immediately tried to get in the band as a cornet player.
So I had the tryouts there in old Pfeiffer Hall.
I got torn down years and years ago.
I was playing, the bandmaster was a master sergeant at that time, retired master sergeant, big fat guy.
He was trying out cornet players among the freshmen.
And I couldn't read music even.
But I could memorize a tune, so.
He had these freshmen come in and play the same tune, you know, and he'd either reject them or keep them.
It finally came my turn.
I knew the tune by heart, so I went in and rattled it off, and it's cornet, so I was accepted.
You were accepted to the band.
Yeah, couldn't read the music.
That's pretty good.
Now, before you came to A&M,
You had, in other words, you had no idea whatsoever what you wanted to be, I mean as far as a profession was concerned?
I can't, I can't recall any.
One time I thought I'd like to be a doctor, that's about all I remember.
So you didn't really have any firm goals or anything?
I didn't have anything in mind when I went down there, except to
get away from Dial Art and get some more education, that's all.
Okay, so then you went down there, what year did you go down there, was it 1917?
1915, that's right, 1915.
At this time had you formed, or during your time at A&M, had you formed any
ideas about politics?
I mean, had you given any thought to political parties, or?
Well, my dad was, died in the World Democrat.
He lived through the Civil War, and so the slaves freed, and the family impoverished, and he was- You mean your grandfather?
No, my father.
My father was born in 1854.
See, he was 12 years old when the Civil War was over.
I thought you said that your grandfather built up in Dodge City.
Yeah, my grandfather moved from Goliad, or Floresville I believe at that time, up to Dodge City.
and took my father and the other children, you see.
Some of the other children.
So your father was a Democrat?
Yeah, he always said I'd vote.
He hated Yankees and he hated
Republicans, and he said, I'd vote for a yellow dog on a Democratic ticket before I'd vote for a black Republican.
Well, of course that influenced the kids.
Later on, when my older brother was appointed governor of Puerto Rico by Republican Hoover, Dad said, I just can't believe you're a Republican at heart.
And what political philosophy do you interpret here, too?
And now, I'm a Republican.
My wife signed up as a Democrat and I signed up as a Republican, but I'm actually an independent.
I vote for the man, I don't vote for the party.
Do you consider yourself a liberal or a moderate or a conservative?
I consider myself conservative.
I was drawn to Reagan.
Reagan and I worked pretty hard for Goldwater in 1964.
I was on the committee at Clearwater, Florida working for him.
And I contributed money to conservative causes until I'm inundated with letters.
I even get telephone calls from the NCAPAC, National Conservative Political Action Committee, Conservative Caucus, and a dozen others, and I've got this big filing cabinet here.
That's where most of it goes, but I have contributed several hundred dollars towards Republicans in the last two years.
Okay, now let's go back to the A&M.
Okay.
And the military then, did that have, the fact that it was a corps institution, did that have any impact on you for going to A&M?
No.
I had no idea I'd ever be in the Army.
When we got in the war, I came home to help Dad on the ranch.
Before the war, let's talk about what corps or unit were you in?
I was in the band.
I lived in Pfeiffer Hall.
What did you think about, I mean did you work while you were in them?
Did you have any opportunity to?
Yes, I had to work in order to pay for my uniforms and food and so forth.
I worked as a janitor.

I was the janitor in Mitchell Hall for I think about two or three days and then the man in charge called me in and put me in charge of the whole building and I had about six or seven other students under me do the janitorial work on that building.
I did stenographic work for the secretary of the YMCA
I can't think of any other work I did.
Were you employed most of the time when you were there?
Yeah, all the time.
Do you remember how much they paid you?
Do you remember what the wages were back then?
I got two dollars a month first year for playing in the band and they raised it to three dollars.
That was fifty percent increase.
Three dollars a month the second year I was there.
The janitor work seemed to me like I made about $20 a month, but I wouldn't swear to that.
Working for the secretary doing his typing and stenographic work, I can't remember what I was getting.
What did you think of the accommodations?
Oh, that was okay.
After all, it was the oldest hall there, I think.
Yeah, I had one big shower in the building and three of us had a room built for two and things like that, but it didn't bother us.
Were they camping out on that?
Were they in tents out there on the drill field?
No, none of us were in tents.
We were all hours in the building.
How about the food?
The food was good compared to what I was used to.
I got fat on it.
What core outfit?
Oh, you were in the band.
Were you in another outfit too?
No, no.
The band, while the rest were, while the core was drilling, the band was practicing music.
Did you ever learn to read music?
Not much, no.
Still can't.
And make good bandmasters sorry every... What's that, lemonade, honey?
Yes, it's lemonade.
I'll give you something stronger later on.
You're talking to who's normally a very quiet man.
I thought I'd better give you something.
I did.
I sure enjoyed being in the band because I got to travel around with the football team.
See places that I'd heard about from other students, but never been around.
I'd never been around much at that time.
I didn't play.
I played intramural baseball.
I wasn't good enough to be on varsity.
What about the hazing?
Can you tell me about the hazing?
Well, I avoided that quite a bit.
They didn't pick on me, maybe because I was little.
I just kept my mouth shut and tried to be a good fish.
I'd see my roommate one time had his fanny massive bruises from being off with a broomstick.
I thought that was awful.
Did you think that hazing served any purpose?
No, none whatever I think of this.
There's no place there at all, no good purpose that I could see.
Some of those kids, well I know one kid that went crazy.
Tied him to a railroad track.
There's a double track, you see, and the train was coming down the main track.
They tied him to the railroad?
They blindfolded him, tied him to the track where the train was not coming, you see.
But he thought the train was coming around on him.
He went nuts.
He did really?
Did they have to send him home?
I don't know what happened to him.
But he dropped out of A&M?
There was quite a stink about it, I know, at A&M, but he never seemed to be able to stop the hazing there.
I thought that was
hazing was out of place in the university.
They didn't do it over at Texas University where my older brother went.
One of my younger brothers went.
There were four of us going and two of us went to A&M and two to Texas.
There was no hazing value of that over in Texas.
Did you like or dislike being in the Corps?
I liked my two years there.
What did you like about being in the Corps of Cadets?
I got good fellowship, made some good friends.
I got away from that stinging place, Dalhart.
I didn't like Dalhart.
I got to see a lot of
places in Texas I'd never had, never seen, but had heard about.
Had good food.
I had one or two instructors that I was very fond of, especially the English instructor.
Okay, who were they?
Boy, I couldn't call them any now.
I just remember that
He taught me how to write a composition.
I learned a lot from him.
The mathematics I liked until I got into trigonometry.
There's unknown equations in trigonometry that remain unknown to me.
From then on, I never could figure out those things, but I could.
In the final examination, there were 10 questions.
You had to make 70 to pass it.
Three of them were unknown equations.
The three I missed, I made my 70.
I got the other seven right, so I got through all that.
Oh, I liked the...
cutting up the cattle and horses and things like that, what do you call it?
Animal husbandry?
Yeah.
Dissecting?
Yeah, dissecting animals.
That was part of animal husbandry.
So you liked the curriculum in animal husbandry then?
Yeah.
I liked it.
I was glad I chose that course because I don't think I would have been a good engineer.
I don't have a mathematical mind exactly.
Did you dislike anything about being in the Corps?
Only the hazing.
I liked the drills.
I liked the dress parades.
I liked the Yale practice, going to football games.
The only thing I disliked was hazing.
Were you ever in any position of leadership when you were at A&M?
made a sergeant in the band for the third year, but I didn't go back.
I was notified that I'd been chosen to be sergeant, but I didn't go back the third year.
I got into the Army.
When you think back on your career and becoming a general, what ways do you think that going to A&M helped you, and what ways do you think it hurt you?
I don't think it had any effect.
You don't think A&M had any effect?
I can't remember thinking of any effect that my two years at A&M had on it.
If I didn't drill, I didn't drill enough to know how to get from here to there, but I went in the aviation section of the Signal Corps in the Army and
I can't say that A&M had any effect either way, except it taught me how to study, since I had to go to ground school for eight weeks before I started flying.
It taught me how to study.
taught me to obey orders.
Discipline, I think I got very good discipline at A&M.
The band was disciplined just the same as the rest of the corps.
So it seems then that it did have some effect.
Yeah.
So now you're saying that it did have some effect.
Yeah, yeah.
It had a good effect in that way.
It taught me discipline and how to study them.
Do you think it had any effect on the fact that you became a leader?
Yes, because I watched what the other leaders did at A&M and I became
well enough like we made a sergeant, which is about as high as you can get as a junior, but I've always been a leader among the kids, but except at A&M, I can't remember having any followers there.
I had some very fine friends, but
I can't remember any leadership that I did there.
Were there any professional soldiers at A&M that had an effect on you?
They taught me discipline.
There was Colonel Muller, M-U-L-L-E-R.
Lieutenant.
Later became Major General.
I can't think of anyone.
That's my name and some retired sergeants who worked there.
I've been disciplined ever since I was a kid and my parents disciplined me.
So I've learned to be a follower and obey orders.
That's what you have to learn first before you can be a leader.
